  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Preface to the Essentials of Governance
  author: Lee Gyecheon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Those who govern flourish; those who bring chaos perish. Gain and loss are all recorded in histories past. The good we may emulate; the evil we may learn to shun. Thus should exhortation and warning be shown to those who come after. For this reason, I gather the writings of many masters to illuminate ten thousand ages.

    Consider: when we abandoned the knotted-cord records and writing appeared, when we established scribes to preserve our annals, the chronicles of Yao and Shun grew clear—showing us the harmony of their age. The strategies of Kings Wen and Wu likewise reveal the splendor of their peace. Yet when Eastern Zhou weakened, the Seven States warred; Qin relied on cunning and force, and lasted barely two generations. Han honored benevolence and mercy, and endured through countless ages. When Han's fate dimmed, Three Kingdoms rose to claim the throne. When Jin's fortune ended, the Five Barbarians troubled all beneath heaven. Six Dynasties held scattered lands, and the realm split asunder. When isolated Sui swallowed all, the world churned with upheaval. Tang rose twenty sovereigns deep before Five Dynasties succeeded each other. Song transmitted three centuries, then northern invaders came. Then Yuan's grip loosened, and Ming's glory was born.

    Now kingdoms unite or divide—their strength waxes and wanes. Times of order alternate with times of chaos—fortunes lengthen or shorten. Since both good and ill are recorded, surely examples and warnings should all be complete. Yet the scrolls are countless, and few can read them all at once.

    Reverently I consider: Your Majesty advances daily in wisdom, heaven-blessed with sacred intelligence. You study the classics to illuminate the source from which sage-kings govern. You examine the histories to mirror the deeds of past and present. Recognizing that traversing all histories is difficult, you determine to gather them into one work. Deeming this humble scribe not unworthy, you entrust the task of compilation. You command capable scholars to oversee it, gather literary masters to complete it. The principles flow from your sovereign judgment; the arrangement follows no fixed historical form. Looking to ages past, we begin with Zhou and end with Yuan. Turning to our Eastern lands, we start with箕子 and extend to Goryeo.

    We extract from ancient records and gather from tales and legends—capturing both the rise and fall of nations and the virtue or vice of rulers and ministers, the success or failure of governance and the purity or corruption of customs. Whether high or humble, whether near or far among the four quarters—if it touches upon human relations, however small, it is recorded. If it serves the state's order, nothing is omitted. The interpretations of many scholars are interwoven; the discussions of former sages are appended. Comprehensive and complete, this is the great principle by which rulers govern; clear and rigorous, this is the essential canon that history alone conveys to the heart.

    Humbly receiving this great trust, I exhaust my meager labor, that the light of sun and moon may shine forth, and that even the smallest contribution may avail. Though I present only the outline and framework, not all in full detail, yet what meets the eye may awaken the heart—and perhaps serve as a foundation for the way of governance.
  footnotes:
    - Yao and Shun (堯舜) were legendary sage-kings of ancient China, known for virtuous rule.
    - Knotted-cord records (結繩) refers to the ancient practice of recording information through knotted strings before writing was developed.
    - The Five Barbarians (五胡) were non-Han peoples who invaded northern China during the Jin Dynasty.
    - The Six Dynasties (六朝) period saw China divided among competing kingdoms following the Han.
    - Goryeo (高麗) was the Korean kingdom that preceded Joseon, indicating this work was written during or after the Joseon period.
